Garbage Collection in Java — Interview-Ready Explanation
“Garbage Collection in Java is an automatic memory management process handled by the JVM. Its main job is to identify and remove objects that are no longer reachable, freeing up heap memory and preventing memory leaks.”


How GC Works — Step-by-Step
1. Object Allocation
    * Objects are created in the heap using new.
    * References to these objects are stored in the stack.
2. Reachability Analysis
    * GC checks which objects are reachable from active threads, static references, or method stacks.
    * Unreachable objects are marked for collection.
3. Mark-and-Sweep Algorithm
    * Mark: Traverse object graph and mark reachable objects.
    * Sweep: Remove unmarked (unreachable) objects from memory.
4. Compacting (Optional)
    * After sweeping, GC may compact memory to reduce fragmentation.

Types of Garbage Collectors
Java offers several GC algorithms:
GC Type	Best For
Serial GC	Single-threaded, good for small apps
Parallel GC	Multi-threaded, high throughput
CMS (Concurrent Mark-Sweep)	Low pause time
G1 GC	Balanced performance, default in Java 9+
ZGC / Shenandoah	Ultra-low pause time, large heaps


